name: 2-(trifluoromethyl)benzonitrile
Reason: 2-(trifluoromethyl)benzonitrile is a derivative of benzonitrile, which has a melting point of -13.2°C. The introduction of the trifluoromethyl group (–CF3) increases the molecular weight and introduces a strong electron-withdrawing effect, which increases the dipole moment and intermolecular forces. This leads to a higher melting point compared to the parent compound. The trifluoromethyl group is a relatively small and rigid group, which does not significantly affect the molecular symmetry. The net effect is an increase in the melting point due to the electron-withdrawing effect and the increased molecular weight.
